Preheat your #oven to 425Â°F. In a #bowl{}, add @red onion{1/2%onion, thinly sliced}, @garlic{1%clove, grated}, @lime{1/2%lime, zest and juice}, @red wine vinegar{1%tbsp}, @maple syrup{1%tsp, optional}, @cilantro{1/4%cup, minced}, @salt{1%pinch}. Toss together to coat then place in the fridge.

Dry the chickpeas then add to a baking tray with 1 tbsp of @avocado oil and a pinch of @salt. Toss to coat, spread in a single layer and bake for ~{20%minutes}. Cool for ~{5%minutes} then add @garlic powder{1%tsp} and @ground coriander{1/2%tsp}. Toss to coat and bake for ~{10%minutes} or until mostly crispy.

Add @cauliflower{1%head, small, cut into 1 inch pieces} to a separate tray with @garlic powder{2%tsp}, @ground coriander{1%tsp}, @onion powder{1%tsp}, @thyme{1%tsp, dry}, @salt{1%pinch}, and @avocado oil{1-2%tbsp}. Toss to coat then spread out on the tray, placing the florets cut side down. Bake for ~{20%minutes}, toss then return to bake for ~{10%minutes} or ~{15%minutes}.

Place @chipotle peppers{1-2%peppers, from a can with adobo sauce}, @unsweetened plant-based yogurt{1/2%cup}, @vegan mayo{2%tbsp}, @lime{1/2%lime, juice and zest}, @maple syrup{2%tsp}, @garlic{1%clove, grated}, @cilantro{1/4%cup, minced}, and @salt{1%pinch} in a small blender cup and blend to combine. Or finely mince the peppers then whisk everything in a bowl.

Transfer the chickpeas to the tray of cauliflower. Drizzle with a few spoons of the chipotle sauce then toss together with tongs to coat.

Warm a #pita{} and spread with some of the chipotle sauce, then top with @lettuce{2%cups, leaves}, the chickpea-cauliflower mix, and some pickled onions. Wrap and enjoy!